On site being supported by and learning from a wonderful team of Artists on a super fun project. Stay tuned for more ( 🌧️ ❌🚫) @riiisaboogie @annabellepopaart @ceara_____  @chopemdownfilms

Today was super humbling. I thought I’d just be able to rock up and paint my drawings HUGE on the (uneven) floor easy peasy.. but drawing with a brush attached to a long stick ain’t easy. You don’t have any physical connection to the surface like you would with drawing on paper, or even a wall.. (no pressure) plus the paint doesn’t flow. So it was hard work but I think I got the hang of it a little bit by the end. I think 😂 .. also had to be spontaneous, and not just copy the drawings, as the mark making is different but that’s kind of cool I think since the original drawings were spontaneous in the first place. Great to have a brilliant team around me for advice and encouragement @riiisaboogie @annabellepopaart @miki__mu @masoneve @jeremy.filmsmore @ceara_____

I am Very excited to announce that my show SEE WHAT I SEE in collaboration with @ihapp_1 of the @cubs opens to the public this Saturday at @galleryvictorchicago 

A number of years ago I made 3 large drawings from Ian’s POV during game situations at Wrigley field. Seeing as my baseball knowledge was zero, Ian was very involved in helping me with the composition of these pieces and just as importantly explaining to me how it made him feel in those moments. 

During trips to Chicago and attending games I also started to observe and explore the relationships that the fans have with the club and also the wider city. 

SEE WHAT I SEE brings together all of these drawings and paintings - from Ian’s dugout view to the intimate characters and rituals that bind the ball club together.

I will also be doing a residency at @galleryvictorchicago for the summer where I will be continuing to explore the @cubs , it’s fans and the City of Chicago.

I was in London the other week so I stopped into see this mad project I made with one of my dearest friends @paulcopyrightdavis  at the @picturehousecentral 

“The mother of all interlocks” is a bonkers history of film and cinema without looking at actors and films- we researched light and old projectors/cameras and the mechanics@of film making and early pioneers of the art form.. and then we chucked loads of other stuff in as we went. I drew in a whole cinema audience on one wall where I think I added in portraits of the builders (and their family members)

We drew it directly on the walls while there was over 50 builders working trying to finish the build it was chaotic but such fun. 

Like I said it’s completely bonkers but i love it.

If you find youself on Shaftesbury Ave go and have a butchers.. they have a great café too.

🎥 🎞️ 💡

🚨 Happy to announce that my show “ DRAWN TWO CITIES” is now open and @paulsmithdesign gallery on Albermarle St, Mayfair London. 

This is my first time showing in London in 13 years and is a continuation of my creative partnership with Paul and his team. 

I made a body of work in two months inspired by the two cities that have meant so much to me in my career. I made two location drawings from the rivers - the Thames in London and the East River in New York- and then used these to inform additional works.

My entire sketchbook archive is on display too- 15 years of observations in both cities. 

Lastly a huge thanks to Paul and his wonderful team for the help in putting this together with a special thanks to @a_snowball_effect 

I’ve always admired Paul so it’s a huge honor to work together and also so much fun. 

The show is up until end of Jan so please stop in to see it if you are in London.

More soon!

Was so lovely to finally meet @paulsmith  at my show in Albemarle St. I remember when I first got to London in 1999 I would wander around the Floral St shop, not being able to affford anything - but always getting nourishment creatively. There was always so much cool stuff to look at- from the shop fittings to the curated trinkets and treasures, jewelry and art. I am so happy that our paths crossed many years later, we both share a similar outlook - that you can find inspiration anywhere if you are inquisitive and keep your 👀 peeled! Thanks Paul and team, appreciate the ongoing creative partnership. @paulsmithdesign

As part of my show DRAWN TwO CITIES at @paulsmithdesign gallery on Albemarle St London,
I have my sketchbook archive on display - mostly made up of drawings from London and New York over the last 10 years.. go check them out if you are in London :)

A bit of a longer look at some of the drawings I am showing at @paulsmithdesign gallery on Albemarle St in London. 

I put this work together in 2 months, working on location in London and New York- choosing the river as my vantage point in both cities. 

Some other work from my archive, as well as my sketchbooks are also on display. 

The show is up till mid jan so go and see it you are in London!

Here’s a little bit about the t shirt collaboration with @paulsmithdesign 

When I was putting this show together I found that memories of London would pop into my head, so I made a note of them, however silly or random they were.
I then made drawings to represent these memories and mixed them together with old London drawings from my books.

I then worked with Paul and his team to extract some of these memories and place them on the T-shirt.

I am really happy with how they came out, it’s super fun.

I know we sold out online, but I think some@are still available in the Albemarle store.
Have a look at the previous post for some more background and info, but  here’s me wearing the black t shirt collaboration with @paulsmithdesign
